Floor

While floor sleeping is uncommon in Western culture, sleeping in the floor is widely practiced in parts of Asia and Islamic world. Often, people would sleep on top of padded blankets to provide for slight cushion, but some actually would sleep without any toppers.


Some example of heavy topper. It is almost like a mattress. However, it is equally common to sleep only with light or no topper.

Cultural difference plays large role in the idea of floor sleeping. In the Western culture, sleeping in the floor is portrayed as sanitarily undesirable as compared to regular bed. This perception is largely due to the fact that wearing shoes inside of the house is the regular practice. When shoes are worn inside of the house, dusts and other dirt inevitably follows inside of the house, even to the bedroom. Under such environment, sleeping on the floor near dust would not be wanted; rather, beds that elevates the sleeping position would be more suitable since it displaces person away from the dusty floor.

This is not the case for many Asian civilization where not wearing shoes inside of bedroom or even entire house is the common practice. In such settings, floor will not be as dusty, and, therefore, more suited to sleep directly on floor. In fact, other activities beyond sleeping are often practiced on floor. For example, floor-sitting desks are common, and so are tea or dining tables for floor sitting.

However, cleaner floor isn't the only reason behind the development of floor-centric cultures. Most notable is the heating. For Korean homes, it almost always comes with mechanism for heating the floor, called Ondol. This is contrary to other hoses that have heating system that either radiates heat from walls(like radiators) or using hot air(heaters we have in Texas). With main source of heat being at the floor, it became norm for people to not only sleep but also do other activities in floor where they can sleep with more warmth--like below gentlemen talking to each other while sitting in floor.


Old houses used to heat using fire places outside the house, but modern houses and apartments developed other ways of heating floor. Almost all Korean houses, new and old will have floor heating. Japan does not have similar heating system, but they tends to have less severe winters as compared to Korea.

Today, more westernized younger generation frequently adopted to use beds instead. Floor is more popular among older generation. For those who wants a bed while also wants to get the affect of sleeping in floor, there are some "rock beds" that replicates feel of sleeping in floor while using a bed. These often also replicates the floor heating as well on the rock surface.
